'''Simon David Buckingham''' (born in Oxford, England) is an [[England|English]] [[information society]] theorist and the originator of the term [[unorganisation]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}
Buckingham has been based in New York since 2005.

== Biography ==

Buckingham created and published in 1996 the unorganisation philosophy. Subsequently, he became a [[serial entrepreneur]].
He founded his first start up in 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobilestreams.com/company_simon_buckingham.php|title=Management Team|publisher=Mobile Streams|accessdate=11 September 2010}}</ref> Mobile Lifestreams, which started out as a research and consulting company.  
Buckingham authoring the "Yes 2 SMS" report that accurately predicted the success of the SMS text messaging service.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/2936685.stm|title=How mobiles made me|publisher=BBC | first=Laura|last=Cummings|date=1 May 2003}}</ref> Buckingham registered and launched the domain name and service ringtones.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobile-ent.biz/features/345/How-to-turn-20-into-over-100m|title=How to turn £20 into over £100m|publisher=Intent Media}}</ref> Mobile Lifestreams was renamed Mobile Streams and completed its [[Initial Public Offering]] in February 2006 (LSE:MOS).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/prices-and-markets/stocks/summary/company-summary.html?fourWayKey=GB00B0WJ3L68GBGBXAIMI|title=MOS Mobile Streams PLC|publisher=London Stock Exchange}}</ref> At the same time, [[Liberty Media]], the U.S. content company became a strategic investor in the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertymedia.com/capital-mobile-streams.aspx|title=Mobile Streams within Liberty Media Capital Group|publisher=Liberty Media}}</ref>

In January 2006, Buckingham become the CEO of [[Zoombak]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zoombak.com/about/executive-team/|title=Executive Team|publisher=Zoombak|accessdate=11 September 2010}}</ref> a provider of GPS devices and services for family safety and enterprise applications. Zoombak is owned by Liberty Media but managed by Buckingham and Mobile Streams. More than 100,000 Zoombak devices had been shipped by October 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zoombak.com/zoombak-ships-100,000th-locator/|title=Zoombak Ships 100,00th Personal GPS Locator|publisher=Zoombak}}</ref>

In 2010, Buckingham founded his third start up in New York, [[Appitalism]], an open [[Digital distribution platform|app store]], that launched in September 2010 in 51 countries.

